FedLogic: Interpretable Federated Multi-Domain Chain-of-Thought Prompt Selection for Large Language Models

Pengwei Xing1, Songtao Lu2, Han Yu1
Abstract

Leveraging “chain-of-thought (CoT)” reasoning to elicit rapid and precise responses from large language models (LLMs) is rapidly attracting research interest. A notable challenge here is how to design or select optimal prompts. The process of prompt selection relies on trial and error, involving continuous adjustments and combinations of input prompts by users based on the corresponding new responses generated from LLMs. Furthermore, minimal research has been conducted to explore how LLMs employ the mathematical problem-solving capabilities learned from user interactions to address issues in narrative writing. To improve interpretability and explore the balance principle between generality and personalization under a multi-domain CoT prompt selection scenario, we propose the Federated Logic rule learning approach (FedLogic). We introduce a theoretical formalization and interactive emulation of the multi-domain CoT prompt selection dilemma in the context of federated LLMs. We cast the problem of joint probability modeling as a bilevel program, where the CoT prompt selection intricacy can be likened to a fuzzy score-based rule selection with the LLMs function as rule generators. FedLogic solves this problem through variational expectation maximization (V-EM). In addition, we incorporate two KL-divergence constraints within this probabilistic modeling framework to surmount the intricacies of managing extensive search spaces and accomplishing cross-domain personalization of CoTs. To the best of our knowledge, FedLogic is the first interpretable and principled federated multi-domain CoT prompt selection approach for LLMs.

Introduction

In recent years, the rapid advancement of natural language processing (NLP) technologies has led to the emergence of large language models (LLMs), such as GPT-3 (Brown et al. 2020) (Generative Pre-trained Transformer 3) and its variants. Their ability to generate coherent and contextually relevant responses has sparked significant interest and enthusiasm in both academia and industry. The underlying mechanism that drives the impressive performance of LLMs lies in their capacity to capture intricate patterns and relationships in vast amounts of textual data. The result is the strong ability to mimic human-like language use and generate plausible texts in a wide range of contexts.

Despite their success, LLMs remain black-boxes in terms of understanding their internal processes and decision-making rationale. The parameters of the top performing LLMs are not available to the public either. This has led to the current LLM research landscape with the majority of the effort focusing on black-box-injection work without formal theory. In-context learning(Brown et al. 2020) (ICL) has been researched in few-shot learning (Min et al. 2022, 2021) in the early stage and recently is being used to describe this mainstream technique for improving LLMs models based on open-domain text (Chowdhery et al. 2022; Zhang et al. 2022), in contrast to the previous BERT-based methods (Devlin et al. 2018) where fine-tuning of model parameters was the prevailing approach. Most of the existing ICL works are interfacing with different kinds of learning tasks (Garg et al. 2022; Laskin et al. 2022; Müller et al. 2021) and implicit properties (Xie et al. 2021; Chan et al. 2022).

The chain-of-thought (CoT) is a representative research pillar of the field of ICL. It injects the inferred steps of the natural language description associated with the problem into LLMs along with the labels to enhance tasks with high inferential demands (Wei et al. 2022). Gao et al. 2023 injects the code descriptions associated with the inference and subsequently when relaying a code runtime to obtain more accurate results. Multi-prompt ensemble-based research has also emerged to ensure answer consistency (Wang et al. 2022). Prompt selection has branched out into a variety of approaches under ICL, including prompt tuning with a prompt-target parameter (Lester, Al-Rfou, and Constant 2021), leveraging separated LLMs to select prompt (Zhou et al. 2022), and reinforcement learning based prompt selection (Su et al. 2022). The aforementioned study has empirically verified the effectiveness of CoTs.

However, the prevailing approach for CoT prompt selection is through trial and error. The process typically involves continuous adjustments and combinations of input prompts by users based on the corresponding new responses generated by LLMs (Yang et al. 2022; Akyürek et al. 2023). Moreover, there is limited investigation on how LLMs utilize the mathematical problem-solving CoTs inference ability acquired from user interactions to provide CoTs answer for the domain of narrative composition. It involves a cross-domain and one-to-many federated trade-off between the specificity and generality of the logical abilities of LLMs.

To bridge this gap, we propose the Federated Logic rule learning approach (FedLogic) for multi-domain LLM CoT prompt selection. It is a first-of-its-kind transformer-based in-context learner designed to simultaneously provide a principled approach for multi-domain LLM CoT prompt selection while enhancing the interpretability and adaptability of LLMs. Cross domain in-context learning requires LLMs to balance generalization with specialization. This problem can be solved by applying a new variational distribution that transforms the general latent variance probability model into a specialized latent variance probability model. This is equivalent to solving a non-i.i.d. federated learning (FL) (Tan et al. 2022) optimization problem when CoTs come from multiple non-i.i.d. domain. We design the transformer as a latent-variance logic rule learner, and formalize the CoTs as logic rules. The transformer-based rule learner competes with the CoTs rule selector in the manner of bilevel learning with variational expectation maximization (V-EM) (Tzikas, Likas, and Galatsanos 2008). This framework leverages two Kullback–Leibler (KL) divergence based constraints in a probabilistic modeling perspective to address the challenges of the large search space and cross-domain personalization of CoTs.

To the best of our knowledge, FedLogic is the first interpretable and principled multi-domain CoT prompt selection approach supporting federated LLMs. In experiment, we focus on exploring the cross-domain CoT representational ability on a designed dataset under cross-visible distribution among different clients to understand how LLMs use the mathematical CoT reference ability to generate narrative composition CoTs. We also extend the state-of-the-art baseline from (Ru et al. 2021) to handle one-to-many complexities equivalently. Extensive experiments demonstrate our model’s superior performance even when the baseline has been further optimized. Our design to leverage KL-divergence has led to enhanced outcomes on both seen and unseen data. Additionally, we undertake a thorough evaluation of our model’s inference capabilities through simulations on real data, using golden first-order logical predicates. The results demonstrate its effectiveness in providing interpretable multi-domain CoT prompt selection for LLMs in a federated manner.

The Proposed FedLogic Approach

In this paper, we focus on the application scenario of federated multi-domain CoT prompt selection. We assume that there is a pool of CoT prompts from multiple domains accumulated from previous interactions with LLMs. When a user wishes to interact with the LLMs, he/she first has to select the CoT prompt from the prompt pool which best suits his/her task. Instead of trial and error, the user can query the CoT prompt pool based on his/her local data (which is potentially sensitive and requires data privacy protection). The FedLogic serves as an approach to accomplish such a search and matching task in an explainable manner.

Without loss of generality, we assume that the ICL query-answer system is a one-to-many bilevel system. The in-context learner is on the upper-level (FL server) side, and the example of query, CoTs, and labels come from multiple lower-level (FL client) sides. n𝑛n denotes the number of clients. This is because when the examples of multiple lower-level sides are independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.), the CoTs belong to the same domain. This is equivalent to traditional single-domain ICL. When each lower-level side handles a non-i.i.d. task, the CoTs are from multiple different domains. This setting enables us to study the interplay between generalization and personalization in ICL.

Since CoTs are the sequence of reasoning steps, it is natural to treat them as logic rules. We formalize a CoT rule as a latent variable z𝑧z. The CoT sample of client i𝑖i is denoted as rule zisubscript𝑧𝑖z_{i}. 𝒛𝒛\boldsymbol{z} denotes the global rule to be learned by the server. We use q1:nsubscript𝑞:1𝑛q_{1:n} to denote each query qisubscript𝑞𝑖q_{i} in a client-specific knowledge graph 𝒢isubscript𝒢𝑖\mathcal{G}_{i} (i.e., qi∼𝒢isimilar-tosubscript𝑞𝑖subscript𝒢𝑖q_{i}\sim\mathcal{G}_{i}). Then, a query qisubscript𝑞𝑖q_{i} (used to emulate a question for an LLM) is equivalent to a possible ⟨h,?,t⟩ℎ?𝑡\langle h,?,t\rangle in 𝒢isubscript𝒢𝑖\mathcal{G}_{i}, and the corresponding answer aisubscript𝑎𝑖a_{i} (used to emulate an answer from an LLM) is the corresponding relation r𝑟r. Algorithm Design for FedLogic

The details of the overall bi-level based CoTs (rule) selection approach of FedLogic is shown in Algorithm 1. In Line 5 and Line 12, the algorithm only transmits the rule probability values and the new rules between each FL client and the FL server. In Lines 13-14, the server generates samples from the received posterior distribution, and adds them to the training set for the server model to access client information. Similarly, in Lines 5-7), each client only receives the new rules to initialize the weight and update wisubscript𝑤𝑖w_{i}. None of them need direct access to each other’s data, which is in line with the requirement of federated learning.

Experimental Evaluation

Experiment Settings

Dataset.

To comprehensively evaluate the performance of FedLogic, we utilize a document-level DWIE (Document-Level Web Information Extraction) dataset (Zaporojets et al. 2021) that has been pre-processed following the methods outlined in (Ru et al. 2021). This dataset contains detailed word type statistics, particularly named entity recognition (NER) categories, for all selected entity words within news articles. It encompasses 101010 different NER categories. The dataset also features annotated relationships between entities, spanning a total of 656565 relationship categories. We leverage these relation annotations among entities to formulate a relation prediction task.

The dataset comprises 799799799 documents in total, categorized into 101010 NER types. These documents are distributed across 444 FL clients, with each client containing 200200200 documents, except for the last client, which holds 199199199 documents. Within each client, the documents are further divided into training and testing subsets, maintaining a 3:1:313:1 ratio.

Cross-Domain Testing Setup.

we design a cross-visible distribution multi-domain testing setup to investigate how LLMs utilize the mathematical problem-solving CoTs inference ability acquired from user interactions to give the CoTs answer for the domain of narrative composition. To be specific, each client is equipped with three distinct sub-datasets: a seen training set, a seen testing set, and an unseen set. Notably, the distribution of the unseen set differs from that of the seen sets and is excluded from model training. Meanwhile, each client’s unseen testing data has same distribution with the seen training data in the neighboring clients. For this, we partition the 101010 NER categories into two groups, each containing 555 categories. These categories are subsequently cross-combined to yield 444 unique category combinations, aligned with the 444 head-tail combinations for the 444 clients, respectively. A key aspect of our approach involves ensuring that each client’s seen set is misaligned with the unseen set by one category. This means that each client’s unseen testing data is the seen training data in the neighboring clients. This strategy results in the creation of 444 non-i.i.d. datasets, each characterized by different head-tail NER category combinations. A client’s seen rule representation can help build other clients’ unseen rule representations.

Learning Task.

The primary experimental task is to emulate the question-and-answer process of LLMs using CoTs centered around knowledge graph (KG) relationship prediction. Within this context, a ⟨h,?,t⟩ℎ?𝑡\langle h,?,t\rangle structure alongside its associated r𝑟r (rh​e​a​dsubscript𝑟ℎ𝑒𝑎𝑑r_{head}) within a KG triplet corresponds to a question-and-answer scenario mimicking user-LLM interactions. Importantly, all feasible paths connecting hℎh to t𝑡t serve as CoTs, symbolizing the logical rule bodies to be acquired.

As illustrated in Figure 1, the knowledge graph relations are mapped from the semantic domain to the named entity recognition (NER) domain. In the semantic space, the elementary unit is r𝑟r (rh​e​a​dsubscript𝑟ℎ𝑒𝑎𝑑r_{head}), determined by a specific head node and tail node. Through projection into the NER space, the fundamental element becomes a path (rule body), contingent on the NER attributes of both the head and tail nodes, in addition to the intermediary rh​e​a​dsubscript𝑟ℎ𝑒𝑎𝑑r_{head} relation. To illustrate, in Figure 1(b), employing the amalgamation of the red NER category, green category, and relation a𝑎a (rule head) as the query within the NER space, multiple feasible paths [(b,c),(e,a,c)]𝑏𝑐𝑒𝑎𝑐[(b,c),(e,a,c)] are associated with a𝑎a. These rule bodies, along with the corresponding NER query, emulate user inputs akin to CoTs for LLMs, as depicted in Figure 1(a).

Due to the non-uniqueness of rule bodies, it becomes imperative to employ a stochastic optimization model for learning the latent variables within the NER space. As demonstrated in Figure 1 (c), at the upper level, a transformer-based rule generator is harnessed to learn and produce numerous potential paths (rule bodies). These generated candidates are subsequently disseminated to the lower-level rule selector. This design choice mitigates the necessity for extensive local search operations to uncover paths within a vast search space. For LLMs, this translates to users being spared the ordeal of iteratively composing CoTs and, instead, directly accessing effective CoTs by a small selection of choices furnished by the LLMs through personalized local knowledge, as depicted in Figure 1 (c).

The Upper-Level Model.

For the upper-level rule generator, we employ a transformer-based model. The role of the rule generator is to utilize the query path r𝑟r to sequentially generate each relation within the equivalent path r1∧⋯∧rlsubscript𝑟1⋯subscript𝑟𝑙r_{1}\wedge\dots\wedge r_{l}. The transformer architecture, renowned for its efficacy in generating sequential outputs such as translations (Vaswani et al. 2017), proves fitting for this task. Additionally, it provides a probability measure of rule generation.

To realize the transition from pθsubscript𝑝𝜃p_{\theta} to p~θsubscript~𝑝𝜃\tilde{p}_{\theta} within the upper-level objective function of Eq. (5), involving the projection into the NER (logic) space, a novel approach is designed. Instead of only inputting the rule head r𝑟r embedding into a conventional transformer-based model, the embeddings of the NER categories for the head and tail nodes are also incorporated. These embeddings are amalgamated with the r𝑟r embedding to form the input embedding for the transformer. This strategic inclusion of the head-tail NER embeddings empowers the transformer-based model to project into the NER rule space. This, in turn, signifies a transformation from a general transformer-based next-word learner into a transformer-based rule generator, as exemplified in the upper level of Figure 1(c). It mirrors the progression from the general state to an in-context session within LLMs, as depicted in the upper level of Figure 1(a).

The Lower-Level Model.

The local model’s responsibility is straightforward. Upon the upper-level rule generator producing N𝑁N potential rule bodies, the local model employs the label of the rule head to update wisubscript𝑤𝑖w_{i}. This update facilitates the selection of the optimal rule body for rh​e​a​dsubscript𝑟ℎ𝑒𝑎𝑑r_{head}, and entails traversing each r𝑟r from 111 to l𝑙l along the path of this rule body r1∧⋯∧rlsubscript𝑟1⋯subscript𝑟𝑙r_{1}\wedge\dots\wedge r_{l}. Subsequently, a pre-trained embedding value derived from (Zhou et al. 2021) is employed as the corresponding fuzzy values. These values serve to derive a fresh score for rh​e​a​dsubscript𝑟ℎ𝑒𝑎𝑑r_{head}. This process emulates LLM users’ evaluation of the LLMs’ answer CoTs and their subsequent feedback regarding the perceived correct answer (Figure 1).

Cross-Domain Personalization between Upper Level and Lower Level.

An additional noteworthy concern illustrated in Figure 1 necessitates resolution between the upper-level and lower-level models. Specifically, the challenge pertains to the non-i.i.d. nature of CoTs across domains. Merging CoTs or rules from divergent distributions within the same server model does not guarantee effective representation learning for rules across disparate distributions. Alternatively, rules commonly learned by a universal server might not be suitable for specific user contexts. To address this, a KL-divergence term is incorporated as a regularization mechanism into the lower-level objective function. This strategic integration facilitates a balance between the extent of generalization and specialization for the rule model.

Model Setup.

The transformer model at the server encodes NER categories and relations through unique numerical identifiers. The embedding layer size for relations is (256,2​R+1)2562𝑅1(256,2R+1), with R𝑅R representing the number of relations (65 in this case). Similarly, the NER category embedding layer has dimensions (256,10)25610(256,10), reflecting the 10 distinct NER categories. The model contains two encoding and decoding layers, and an output layer of size (256,2​R+1)2562𝑅1(256,2R+1). The input for the transformer is obtained by concatenating a rule head and a rule body, both of size 4. Any shortfall is supplemented with padding symbols and masked using a 4×4444\times 4 position mask. Each rule head generates a set of 50 rule bodies on average, and these candidates are then transmitted to the lower-level model, with duplicates removed.

On the client side, the rule selector model dynamically initializes the weights for each communication round. These weights are tailored to the candidate rule bodies originating from the upper level, with their variability stemming from the stochastic nature of the upper-level optimization process and the probabilistic characteristics of the generated rules. The weight group size is denoted as (K,N×1)𝐾𝑁1(K,N\times 1), where K𝐾K is the number of rule head categories. Each weight group member corresponds to a candidate rule body, with its dimensions as N×1𝑁1N\times 1. The value of N𝑁N is not fixed due to the exclusion of duplicate candidate rule bodies.

Results and Discussion

In order to conduct a rigorous assessment, we extend the state-of-the-art baseline of (Ru et al. 2021) from traditional one-to-one to handle one-to-many complexities equivalently to investigate the role of the KL divergence with probability-based constraints between the upper and lower levels. In scenarios where rule-based decision-making is employed, the local model can exhibit oscillations and fail to converge due to the dynamic nature of the process. The inclusion of a KL divergence constraint mitigates this phenomenon. Evaluation of overall performance is based on metrics averaged across all clients. We compare the outcomes of two sets of experiments using F1-scores on both the Unseen and Seen testing data. “W/O. KL” and “W. KL” denote experiments conducted without (the method of (Ru et al. 2021)) and with KL-divergence constraints (FedLogic), respectively.

The results in Figure 2 show that introducing a KL-divergence constraint to both the Seen and Unseen testing data groups leads to convergence at higher F1-scores. Conversely, the Unseen testing data group without KL-divergence adjustment achieves convergence but at lower F1-scores. The Seen testing data group without KL-divergence constraint exhibits oscillations and does not achieve convergence under the same conditions. Additionally, we analyze the impact of varying KL coefficients on F1 score results for the Unseen dataset. The results in Figure 3 demonstrate that different coefficients indeed influence the personalization performance.

To assess the logical reasoning capabilities of FedLogic, we adopt the 39 golden first-order logic predicates from the DWIE dataset (Zaporojets et al. 2021) for consistency checks after updates by the rule selector model in the lower level, following (Ru et al. 2021). These predicates include atomic formulas such as m​e​m​b​e​r​_​o​f​(X,Y)∧s​p​o​r​t​_​p​l​a​y​e​r​(X)→p​l​a​y​e​r​_​o​f​(X,Y)→𝑚𝑒𝑚𝑏𝑒𝑟_𝑜𝑓𝑋𝑌𝑠𝑝𝑜𝑟𝑡_𝑝𝑙𝑎𝑦𝑒𝑟𝑋𝑝𝑙𝑎𝑦𝑒𝑟_𝑜𝑓𝑋𝑌member\_of(X,Y)\wedge sport\_player(X)\rightarrow player\_of(X,Y). Logic accuracy is evaluated by plugging predicted relationships from the test set into the rule head and body, respectively. The logic accuracy curves in Figure 4 correspond to the four groups of experiments mentioned earlier. Consistency with the F1 score results shown in Figure 2 is evident, with the group exhibiting oscillations achieving the lowest logic accuracy. The groups with KL-divergence constraints achieve higher logic accuracy compared to the groups without such constraints.

Related Work

FedLogic vs. Transformer-based ICL.

Akyürek et al.2023 also leverages transformers as theory-complete small approximate models to investigate the principle of in-context learning. The model addresses linear regression tasks and is used to gain insights into transformer predictor behaviors. The corresponding optimization problem is defined as:

Secondly, our query q1:nsubscript𝑞:1𝑛q_{1:n} comes from a non-i.i.d. multi-domain 𝒢1:nsubscript𝒢:1𝑛\mathcal{G}_{1:n} (i.e., our problem is a more complex one-to-many problem). Thirdly, compared to using a linear regression function, we leverage the V-EM theory to build a posterior function z∗superscript𝑧z^{*} to denote the CoTs with a probability model. With these advantages, FedLogic can serve more general and complex scenarios.

FedLogic vs. Bilevel Federated Learning.

Bilevel FL (Xing et al. 2022) is a general paradigm that enables federated personalization. Meta-learning-based FL (T Dinh, Tran, and Nguyen 2020) is a special case of it. Bilevel FL retains the scalability of the FL server, while removing the requirement for the upper and lower tasks to possess identical problem dimensions in meta-learning-based FL. They employ shared weights at the upper level as the global knowledge and the weights of the lower-level clients as local knowledge. Federated personalization is achieved by imposing constraints on these two sets of weights. The bilevel FL problem can be formalized as follows:

minθsubscript𝜃\displaystyle\min_{\theta}\; ℓ​(θ)=f​(θ,{wi∗​(θ)|i∈{1,…,n}})ℓ𝜃𝑓𝜃conditional-setsuperscriptsubscript𝑤𝑖𝜃𝑖1…𝑛\displaystyle\ell(\theta)=f(\theta,\{w_{i}^{*}(\theta)|i\in\{1,...,n\}\})
s. t. wi∗​(θ)∈arg​minwi⁡gi​(θ,wi)+ℛ​(θ,wi),superscriptsubscript𝑤𝑖𝜃subscriptargminsubscript𝑤𝑖subscript𝑔𝑖𝜃subscript𝑤𝑖ℛ𝜃subscript𝑤𝑖\displaystyle w_{i}^{*}(\theta)\in\operatorname*{arg\,min\,}_{w_{i}}g_{i}(\theta,w_{i})+\mathcal{R}(\theta,w_{i}),\vspace{-2mm} (17)

where f​(⋅)𝑓⋅f(\cdot) and gi​(⋅)subscript𝑔𝑖⋅g_{i}(\cdot) are the upper and lower level objective functions determined by θ𝜃\theta and wisubscript𝑤𝑖w_{i}, respectively. ℛℛ\mathcal{R} is a regularization term serving as a constraint between upper and lower level weights.

Following this notation, our problem can be re-written as:

minθsubscript𝜃\displaystyle\min_{\theta} ℒTθ​(θ,{z​(wi∗​(θ))|i∈{1,…,n}})subscriptℒsubscript𝑇𝜃𝜃conditional-set𝑧superscriptsubscript𝑤𝑖𝜃𝑖1…𝑛\displaystyle\mathcal{L}_{T_{\theta}}(\theta,\{z({w_{i}}^{*}(\theta))|i\in\{1,...,n\}\})
s. t. wi∗(θ)∈arg​minwi∼𝒛θ−𝔼p~ilogpwi+λKL(p~wi||p~θ).\displaystyle w_{i}^{*}(\theta)\in\operatorname*{arg\,min\,}_{w_{i}\sim\boldsymbol{z}_{\theta}}-\mathbb{E}_{\tilde{p}_{i}}\log p_{w_{i}}+\lambda\textrm{KL}(\tilde{p}_{w_{i}}||\tilde{p}_{\theta}).

Comparing these two formulations, we can observe two key differences. Firstly, wi∼𝒛θsimilar-tosubscript𝑤𝑖subscript𝒛𝜃w_{i}\sim\boldsymbol{z}_{\theta} denotes that the wisubscript𝑤𝑖w_{i} belongs to rule space from the upper level. This means that FedLogic is compatible with various dynamic weighting FL schemes. Secondly, when the weights are dynamic, the use of weights as a medium for regularization in traditional methods is not applicable. FedLogic demonstrates its superiority by utilizing the prior and posterior distributions of latent variables as a medium for constraining their KL-divergence (i.e., the role of KL(p~wi||p~θ)\textrm{KL}(\tilde{p}_{w_{i}}||\tilde{p}_{\theta})).

FedLogic vs. Neural-Symbolic Learning.

The most related works from neural symbol learning are (Ru et al. 2021) and (Qu et al. 2020). The problem for both of them can be denoted as pw​(a|z,q,𝒢)​pθ​(z|q)subscript𝑝𝑤conditional𝑎𝑧𝑞𝒢subscript𝑝𝜃conditional𝑧𝑞{p_{w}(a|z,q,\mathcal{G})p_{\theta}(z|q)}, while our problem is defined in Eq. (The Proposed FedLogic Approach). Comparing these two formulations, there are two major differences. Firstly, our problem is one-to-many rather compared to their one-to-one problem scenario. Secondly, our hidden variable is jointly inferred with queries from n𝑛n clients (i.e., 𝒛|∪i=1nqi)\boldsymbol{z}|\cup_{i=1}^{n}q_{i}) in contrast to their hidden variable z|qconditional𝑧𝑞z|q). Note that under the FL setting, the non-i.i.d. issue is common. Therefore, our work is better suited for practical FL scenarios.

Conclusions

In this paper, we proposed a first-of-its-kind rule-based one-to-many transformer-based in-context learning approach enabling users with sensitive local data to collaboratively learn how to select the most appropriate CoT prompts. It enhances the interpretability of LLMs from the perspective of up-down interactions, in contrast to previous works which solely focused on the role of the transformer. In addition, our approach expands the horizon of FL research, empowering researchers to address the challenge of model fusion in decision-making tasks with dynamic weights, as well as tackling the non-i.i.d. problem by modeling the server rule decisions as probabilistic hidden variables. Our framework is a novel one-to-many approach, distinguishing itself from traditional one-to-one neural symbolic reasoning systems.

A example to showcase the logic-rule-based federated learning for CoTs learning emulation

While we demonstrated in our experiments, using logic accuracy curves above, how rule-based federated learning can facilitate both cross-domain CoTs generalization and specialization learning between common server and different clients, an example is still needed to illustrate the scenario of our rule-based cross-domain federated learning approach for CoTs learning emulation. Table 1 encompasses all the first-order logic rule predicates involved in the dataset. In this section, we provide a vivid example based on these rule predicates from the table as shown in the Figure 5:

  • •

    For the generalization in common server-side: In common server, certain implicit shared rule (CoTs) representations are learned, such as the implied representation of the rule head m​e​m​b​e​r​_​o​f𝑚𝑒𝑚𝑏𝑒𝑟_𝑜𝑓member\_of. Specifically, different clients from various domains will upload different but similar rule feedbacks for m​e​m​b​e​r​_​o​f𝑚𝑒𝑚𝑏𝑒𝑟_𝑜𝑓member\_of with different rule bodies. For instance, a document from press releases contribute and upload rules like ”s​p​o​k​e​s​p​e​r​s​o​n​_​o​f→m​e​m​b​e​r​_​o​f→𝑠𝑝𝑜𝑘𝑒𝑠𝑝𝑒𝑟𝑠𝑜𝑛_𝑜𝑓𝑚𝑒𝑚𝑏𝑒𝑟_𝑜𝑓spokesperson\_of\rightarrow member\_of” and a document about sports events provide rules like ”c​o​a​c​h​_​o​f→m​e​m​b​e​r​_​o​f→𝑐𝑜𝑎𝑐ℎ_𝑜𝑓𝑚𝑒𝑚𝑏𝑒𝑟_𝑜𝑓coach\_of\rightarrow member\_of”. Through these two similar rules, the rule learner within the federated server can acquire common prior information, namely, that membership represents a type of affiliation relationship pertaining to human beings.

  • •

    For the personalization of different client-side: when a client submits a query (pertaining to a particular person) along with a prompting rule ”i​n​s​t​i​t​u​t​i​o​n​_​o​f→p​a​r​t​_​o​f→𝑖𝑛𝑠𝑡𝑖𝑡𝑢𝑡𝑖𝑜𝑛_𝑜𝑓𝑝𝑎𝑟𝑡_𝑜𝑓institution\_of\rightarrow part\_of” (i.e., a question and a CoTs), the local rule selector will project them into logic rule space and sent a rule query (a type of affiliation relationship pertaining to human beings) to the server, and the server generates multiple relevant rules based on this rule query, such as ”c​o​a​c​h​_​o​f→m​e​m​b​e​r​_​o​f→𝑐𝑜𝑎𝑐ℎ_𝑜𝑓𝑚𝑒𝑚𝑏𝑒𝑟_𝑜𝑓coach\_of\rightarrow member\_of” and ”s​p​o​k​e​s​p​e​r​s​o​n​_​o​f→m​e​m​b​e​r​_​o​f→𝑠𝑝𝑜𝑘𝑒𝑠𝑝𝑒𝑟𝑠𝑜𝑛_𝑜𝑓𝑚𝑒𝑚𝑏𝑒𝑟_𝑜𝑓spokesperson\_of\rightarrow member\_of”. Different clients will then select the rules they desire based on their domain knowledge. For instance, individuals in the news domain might identify ”s​p​o​k​e​s​p​e​r​s​o​n​_​o​f→m​e​m​b​e​r​_​o​f→𝑠𝑝𝑜𝑘𝑒𝑠𝑝𝑒𝑟𝑠𝑜𝑛_𝑜𝑓𝑚𝑒𝑚𝑏𝑒𝑟_𝑜𝑓spokesperson\_of\rightarrow member\_of” as the correct rule they seek, while those in the sports domain may opt for ”c​o​a​c​h​_​o​f→m​e​m​b​e​r​_​o​f→𝑐𝑜𝑎𝑐ℎ_𝑜𝑓𝑚𝑒𝑚𝑏𝑒𝑟_𝑜𝑓coach\_of\rightarrow member\_of” as the preferred inference. The auxiliary task(rule selector) will give feedback to the server according to the client’s choice.

  • •

    Data privacy guarantee: From the second point above, we can find that the local auxiliary task(rule selector) will primarily project specific person and example CoTs prompts into a rule space to form a rule query. Optimizing the Fuzzy Function for Posterior

In this section, we strive to enhance our algorithm by refining the optimization process of the fuzzy function. Drawing from Algorithm 1, at the lower level, we utilize eq.(ICL with Cross Domain CoTs) as the objective function for updating wisubscript𝑤𝑖w_{i}. The posterior segment of eq.(ICL with Cross Domain CoTs) is calculated using eq. (12). Before employing label aisubscript𝑎𝑖a_{i} to generate the new posterior, a fuzzy function is applied to the distributed rule bodies from the server. This function calculates the fuzzy score for each rule body (max𝒢​i​∏k∈l​x​(rk​j)subscript𝒢𝑖product𝑘𝑙𝑥subscript𝑟𝑘𝑗\max_{\mathcal{G}i}\prod{k\in l}x(r_{kj})) by maximizing across the entirety of 𝒢isubscript𝒢𝑖\mathcal{G}_{i}. Given the time-intensive nature of this step, optimizing the fuzzy function becomes necessary.

The core concept revolves around utilizing eq. (12) solely for computing the posterior during the initial I𝐼I communication rounds, aiming to establish a fundamental rule generator. In subsequent stages, an innovatively designed path-based fuzzy posterior score function is adopted, replacing the graph-based fuzzy function (max𝒢​i​∏k∈l​x​(rk​j)subscript𝒢𝑖product𝑘𝑙𝑥subscript𝑟𝑘𝑗\max_{\mathcal{G}i}\prod{k\in l}x(r_{kj})) for saving computational time. Consequently, the posterior computation can be written in the following form:

𝔼p~​(zi)pwi(ai|zi,qi,𝒢i)=σ(ai⋅∑jwi​j⋅maxx([r1​j,…rl​j]])),\displaystyle\mathbb{E}_{\tilde{p}(z_{i})}p_{w_{i}}(a_{i}|z_{i},q_{i},\mathcal{G}_{i})=\sigma\bigg{(}a_{i}\cdot\sum_{j}w_{ij}\cdot{\max x([r_{1j},...r_{lj}]])}\bigg{)}, (18)

In the equation above, x​([r1​j,…​rl​j])𝑥subscript𝑟1𝑗…subscript𝑟𝑙𝑗x([r_{1j},...r_{lj}]) symbolizes the fuzzy value (pre-trained embedding value) along the trajectory of rule body r1∧⋯∧rlsubscript𝑟1⋯subscript𝑟𝑙r_{1}\wedge\dots\wedge r_{l}. Furthermore, max⁡x​([r1​j,…​rl​j])𝑥subscript𝑟1𝑗…subscript𝑟𝑙𝑗\max x([r_{1j},...r_{lj}]) represents the novel path-based fuzzy function, which simplifies the process by directly adopting the maximum value among the corresponding fuzzy value along the trajectory of rule body as the comprehensive fuzzy score for the rule body.

For that, our new algorithm is described at Algorithm 2 as follow:

In lines 7-8 of Algorithm 2, when the current round falls within the initial I𝐼I steps, we utilize the graph-based approach max𝒢i​∏k∈lx​(rk​j)subscriptsubscript𝒢𝑖subscriptproduct𝑘𝑙𝑥subscript𝑟𝑘𝑗\max_{\mathcal{G}_{i}}\prod_{k\in l}x(r_{kj}) from Eq. (12) to calculate the posterior fuzzy score across the entire graph 𝒢isubscript𝒢𝑖\mathcal{G}_{i}, solving Eq. (ICL with Cross Domain CoTs). This approach rectifies the rule bodies using local graph path information, aligning the equivalent paths distributed by the server with the true equivalent paths within 𝒢isubscript𝒢𝑖\mathcal{G}_{i}. As a result, the need for time-consuming path searches to rectify deviations in specific equivalent paths is mitigated.

In lines 9-10 of Algorithm 2, it says that once a foundational and relatively stable rule generator is established, there’s no longer a necessity to perform a path search in each round. Instead, the path distributed by the server is directly utilized, selecting the maximum fuzzy value along the path to effectively represent the score of the current path.

Algorithm 2 introduces two notable advantages:

  • •

    Reduce fluctuations between upper-lower levels: The algorithm effectively avoids excessive specializations when the lower level updates the fuzzy values along the trajectory of the rule body of server-distributed rules. Graph-based fuzzy value updating method will result in calculating the fuzzy score totally depending on local specific information which can lead to volatile overall performance fluctuations. As illustrated in Figure 6, plot (b) showcases the F1 values using Algorithm 2, achieving nearly identical performance and reducing fluctuations between upper-lower levels in both Seen and Unseen data scenarios.

  • •

    Reduce time complexity: This algorithm significantly reduces time complexity by only calculating fuzzy values along the trajectory of the rule body but not updating fuzzy values across the graph. More details are in the section on Time Complexity Analysis for Cross-Domain Learning.

Time Complexity Analysis for Cross-Domain Learning

In this section, we first provide an example to showcase the essence of cross-domain learning (FL) under our experiment scenario. As shown in Figure 1(a), using the relation a𝑎a in triplet <5,a,6><5,a,6> as an instance, our goal is to improve the prediction accuracy of relation a𝑎a by finding more new rule bodies (equivalent paths from node 5 to node 6) to infer and update the fuzzy value of rule head a𝑎a. There are two equivalent paths from node 5 to node 6 in domain 1, (b,c)𝑏𝑐(b,c) and (e,a,c)𝑒𝑎𝑐(e,a,c), while there are also two paths (b,c)𝑏𝑐(b,c) and (f,h)𝑓ℎ(f,h) in domain 2, which include a different path (f,h)𝑓ℎ(f,h) that can enable us to obtain new information from another domain. We know that increasing the diversity of samples reduces the error rate and thus improves the accuracy of relationship prediction.

If we want to update all fuzzy values for all edges across these two domains by discovering new equivalent edges, we have the following four options:

  • •

    Deterministic Graph Aggregation

    In this baseline approach, the adjacency matrix and fuzzy values of both domain 1 and domain 2 are transmitted to the server. Subsequently, the server merges the adjacency matrices to create a larger dimensional adjacency matrix along with corresponding relations. The most time-intensive phase is the path search within the merged graph space.

  • •

    Deterministic Rule Aggregation

    In this baseline approach, the time-consuming stage involves performing an intra-domain maximum weight path search for each domain (domain 1 and domain 2) using the agreed-upon uniform NER-pair query pair as the start and end points. The resulting paths are then merged on the server based on the uniform NER-pair query pair.

  • •

    Stochastic Rule Aggregation (Algorithm 1)

    In Algorithm 1, an intra-domain path search is confined to paths distributed from the server. This implies that the head-tail pairs are fewer than those in the deterministic rule aggregation approach. Nonetheless, a smaller-scale path search is still necessary.

  • •

    Stochastic Rule Aggregation (Algorithm 2)

    For Algorithm 2, a limited intra-domain path search is only required during the initial I𝐼I rounds.

Sensitivity of adding ratio of posterior sample for upper-level training

To examine whether the incorporation of posterior samples obtained from the lower-level (E-step) can effectively impact the upper-level rule updates in the M-step, we conducted a total of 9 experiments ranging from a sample inclusion ratio of 10%percent1010\% to 90%percent9090\% as shown in the Figure 7. This comparison aimed to assess the varying effects of different ratios on the training loss of the upper-level rule trainer during its first round of training.

The results indicate that a mere increase in the inclusion ratio of posterior samples from 10%percent1010\% to 20%percent2020\% has a substantial effect in reducing the training loss of the upper-level model. Subsequently, as this ratio is uniformly raised, the loss continues to decrease, albeit at a progressively slower rate. The improvement in the upper-level model becomes less pronounced after incorporating around 70%percent7070\% of the posterior samples. This phenomenon provides evidence for the effectiveness of posterior samples in enhancing the upper-level model. The limited impact observed with higher ratios is consistent with the principle that a certain proportion of samples can effectively reflect the contained posterior information; an excessive number of samples could lead to information redundancy.

Sensitivity of upper-level learning rate

In this experiment, we conducted tests using three sets of different learning rates for the upper-level rule learner under two conditions: with KL-divergence constraint and without KL-divergence constraint. These tests were performed on both Seen and Unseen test data to evaluate the impact of the rule generator on the overall game system. As depicted in Figure 8, we observe three phenomena:

  • •

    The first phenomenon is that KL dominance occurs only when the upper level achieves dominance in the upper-lower level game, i.e., a larger upper-lower learning rate. This observation aligns with our formula’s implication that when the lower level’s specialization abilities are in agreement, the group with stronger generalization ability can learn more global prior knowledge at the given learning rate. Consequently, this leads to enhanced overall performance. In cases of insufficient learning rate, the upper-level learning fails to acquire adequate information about the global prior to using the global generalization ability.

  • •

    The second phenomenon is that while the overall F1 value and the overall logic value increase as the upper learning rate increase, the curves of logic accuracy and F1 only exhibit greater consistency when the learning rate is sufficiently high. This finding indicates that the upper level is indeed learning effective rules to improve the overall F1 performance. When the rule learner fails to learn sufficiently, the rules newly distributed from the upper level may not necessarily be effective for the lower level.

  • •

    The third phenomenon is that the gap between the curves corresponding to the two groups, Unseen and Seen, is smaller when the upper layer model employs a lower learning rate. This effect is evident when the upper layer is disadvantaged in the game between the upper and lower layers. This behavior can be observed in both subplots of the F1 values corresponding to (a1) and the logic accuracy values corresponding to (b1), with the latter curve in (b1) almost overlapping. This phenomenon implies that the upper model can differentially generate rules for the Unseen and Seen data, and as this role weakens, the difference between the curves of Seen and Unseen data becomes smaller.
